column1: On 10 December 2019, how many total locations with Combined Charging System (CCS) fast chargers will be installed in the European area?
column5: ['Less than 7,000', 'Between 7,000 and 7,999, inclusive', 'Between 8,000 and 8,999, inclusive', 'Between 9,000 and 9,999, inclusive', '10,000 or more']
column6: ['Technology']
column11: The adoption of electric vehicles is subject to a "chicken and egg" problem where potential consumers want a more extensive charging network, but businesses want more electric cars on the roads to justify building those new charging stations (Reuters, Inside EVs). Europe has gone from zero Combined Charging System (CCS) fast charger locations in 2014 to 5,712 as of 14 December 2018. This question will be suspended on 9 December 2019 and closed using the total installed charger locations listed on 10 December 2019 from the "CCS Charge Map – Europe" website. If during the question's open period the source adds additional countries to the European area list, they will count. Confused? Check our FAQ or ask us for help.

column6: Currently 8074 according to the source I could find. Less than a month to go, and monthly increase is typically ~ 150 this year, so no chance to be < 8000 or > 8999, unless I've used a bad source.
Forecast: 8,209 locations.
At the end of October there are 8074 locations. Recent months have averaged about 175 and there is only one month left. Therefore it seems certain that the total will fall between 8000 and 8999.
Website has updated and now has over 8,000 (barely). Given the limited time frame remaining, it seems highly likely it will remain in the 8,000 to 8,999 bucket.

Decreasing my forecast for 9000-9999 and increasing my forecasts for 7000-7999 and 8000-8999 after rereading the question and noticing that it is based on the websites report on Dec 10, 2019. Website seems a few months behind and that holds historically, so I should decrease my estimates to account for that.

Exactly two months till this one closes. Based on the website [1] there are 7893 in Europe right now, and they have averaged about 200 a month. So, that would suggest about a little over 8,000 by the close date.

Hmmm 7893 as of early October. Assume fewer installed in wetter months as work gets harder and more expensive. No incentives to radically increase install rate. Other things countries want to spend money on.

Almost everybody forecasting this is using statistical methods. Given that the current existing number is 6744 and average monthly increase the higher buckets seem out of reach. The lowest bucket is improbable as well, next month should see it become impossible.

- Current total: 6,879 [1] - Average monthly number of stations added was 241 (past seven months). [1] Using this number, we arrive at ~ 8,807 by mid-December. - We can also model with a growth rate. Average growth rate was 4.1%. Using this number, we arrive at ~9,487 by mid-December. However, the growth rate seems to have increased over that time period by about 22% per month on average. I don't put much stock in that, however, since it fluctuated a lot over that time. - I don't expect new countries to join. UK leaving the EU immediately with a hard Brexit is perhaps 10%. The UK represents 18% of the current total. So I'd want to substract 1.8% from the calculated total: Thus, we arrive at 8,648 and 9,316 respectively. - Standard deviation was about 100 CCS of stations per month.

Updating this forecast based on considering different growth scenarios: - September 2018 (148) for the rest of the time frame: gets to 8086 - this would be the worst case scenario - current rolling average increase (223) for the complete months available for the time frame at the link (Sept 2018 - Feb 2019): gets to 8763 - this is a conservative scenario, but realistic scenario - Feb 2019 increase (393) continues for the rest of the time frame: gets to 10291 - this is the optimistic scenario, not sure if there will be a saturation at some point or if Feb/March 2019 could be upward outliers. This forecast will need an update at the end of April when it is clearer whether the recent acceleration in growth will persist.

Currently at ~6,000. If it stays at current month average of 190, it gets us to 8200. December has 269. If that were the average for the year, that would be 9228. In order to get to 10,000, we'd need to get to a month average of 333. Sliding up a bit.

27 countries including 2 large ones with commitment to decarbonisation (France, Germany) and active ramping up of electric car production in Germany: a ready market in Scandinavia (where renewables are well developed): and an identifiable universe of large retailers with car parks where fast chargers can easily be installed - and are being installed right now. This won't be led by domestic charging points, that comes later, but few supermarkets/local authorities will be blind to the opportunity to 'monetise' a parking space.

It seems unlikely that the financial commitment will show a short-term return on investment. The practicality of the system has not been adequately considered. The reality of shifting the carbon use to another location (where the electricity is generated) has not been adequately investigated. Some countries may illustrate a general commitment to the ethos, thereby increasing installation numbers.

Assume a start of 190 average for the 1st quarter and a 20 increment for each subsequent quarter: 190 + 190 + 190 + 210 + 210 + 210 + 230 + 230 + 230 + 250 + 250 + 250 and 81 for the partial month of December for a total of 2721. Already installed: 5712 + 2721 = 8433.

Both the number of fast charges and the number of electric/plug-in-hybrid cars best fit a quadratic trend (as opposed to linear or exponential). Projecting that out yields between 8,500 and 8,850 by December 10, 2019. And I'll add some scatter around that point.

Since May 2018, the average has been 159 stations per month. Since September, it has been 172/month. The graph in the link indicates a noticeable uptick since about Oct 2017, and a rough estimate would be about 130/mo over the past 15 months, with a pretty steady average before that of about 80/mo.
